    {
      "id": "5a93c517_b2163cf0",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/mso/resources/config/log/filebeat/filebeat.yml",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 24,
      "message": "I agree with Jerome and actually had the same thought, we can technically remove the namespace as they are scoped to the single namespace which is where all the pods are too.\n\nThe only reason to keep it is if we want an app in 1 namespace to talk to an app in another namespace (which isn't something I think makes sense at this point in time).\n\nLet's get the charts done and then try removing it from everywhere in 1 sweeping change testing out the behaviour at the same time.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 131,
        "name": "Mandeep Khinda",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Mandeep.Khinda@gmail.com",
        "username": "mkhinda"
      },
      "updated": "2018-03-26 20:43:46.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "5a93c517_2f2ba331",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "5a93c517_15e7dae5",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/log/charts/log-elasticsearch/templates/pvc.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 21,
      "message": "If you do not specify a rule to select the proper PV and if at the time you are creating the PVC, multiple PV are available you can perfectly end with a PVC bound to a PV coming from another deployment on the same kubernetes cluster. That's why, as a precaution, I would specify a selector to drive the binding process",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 201,
        "name": "Jerome Doucerain",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jerome.doucerain@bell.ca",
        "username": "jdoucerain"
      },
      "updated": "2018-03-26 22:59:32.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "5a93c517_8f02f7b2",
      "unresolved": false
